<br>
However, if the windows look like little system messages - grey boxes with some bit of text and an OK or OK &amp; Cancel buttons only - then it's an exploit used by spammers to send messages via the Windows messenger service.*<br>
<br>
If you're doing this from home, and don't have a full fledged network - with multiple levels of user access and a need to be able to send messages to all workstations at once - there's no need to have this service running.... thankfully, it's easy to turn off.<br>
<br>
If you're using Windows XP or 2000:<br>
Start&gt; Control Panel<br>
Select &quot;Administrative Tools&quot;<br>
Select &quot;Services&quot;<br>
Select &quot;Messenger&quot; (may be called Windows Messenger)<br>
Right Click &gt; Choose properties<br>
Stop the service<br>
Set startup type to manual  or disabled.<br>
<br>
And you're done.  You may need to restart, I can't recall.<br>
<br>
*The Messenger service is used by system administrators to send messages to all workstations or workgroups on a network.  Usually, it'd be used for something like... &quot;Server is coming down in 15 minutes for maintenance, please save your work and log off now.&quot;  On small or home networks, it's usually easier to yell &quot;Get off the damn `pooter!&quot; down the hall... there really is no need for 99.9% of home users to have the service running.  Add to the fact that it is one of the easiest exploits in all creation to spam that service through an port... it's really better off closed.<br>
